column8:
If a base label is decoded that matches the configured base label type and digits of a CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON_CONTROL entry, the configured addon type is also required to be decoded before the base label and addon are transmitted.
This value has 4 fields, 1 nibble each.  The most significant nibble is Nibble [0].  The least significant nibble is Nibble [3].
Nibbles [0] [1] [2] are used to specify the first 3 digits of the base label. Nibble [3] specifies the base label type and also the type of addon that is required.
Values for Nibbles [0] [1] [2] may be 0x0 - 0x9;  0xF = do not care; 0xA - 0xE = indeterminate results.  
Conditional addon settings are considered by the scanner before optional addon settings (CI_ENABLE_OPTIONAL...). If a decoded base label does not match any of the CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON_CONTROL entries, the scanner will then check for applicable optional addon settings.
For situations where a decoded base label matches more than one CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON_CONTROL entry, the scanner will require just one addon type from the matching CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON_CONTROL entries.

column4: Sets the time the scanner will look for an addon when an add-on fragment has been seen and optional add-ons are enabled.
column8:
The "normal" setting for this configuration item is 0x07 (70 milliseconds). To enable optional addons, see CI_ENABLE_OPTIONAL_P2, CI_ENABLE_OPTIONAL_P5.
Value is multiplied by 10 msec step.

column4: Enables optional P2 add-ons.
column8:
If a EAN/UPC base label and a P2 addon are both decoded, the scanner will transmit the base label and addon. If a EAN/UPC base label is decoded without an addon, the base label will be transmitted without an addon. See CI_OPTIONAL_ADDON_TIMER and CI_P2_ADDON_MINIMUM_READ for additional information.
Please note that conditional addons settings (CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON...) are considered by the scanner before optional addon settings.

column4: Enables optional P5 add-ons.
column8:
If a EAN/UPC base label and a P5 addon are both decoded, the scanner will transmit the base label and addon. If a EAN/UPC base label is decoded without an addon, the base label will be transmitted without an addon. See CI_OPTIONAL_ADDON_TIMER and CI_P5_ADDON_MINIMUM_READ for additional information.
Please note that conditional addons settings (CI_CONDITIONAL_ADDON...) are considered by the scanner before optional addon settings.

column4: Specifies the tolerance of the digit classification algorithm for Code 39.
column8: A high value of aggressiveness makes the algorithm more tolerant and able to classify distorted codes. A low value of aggressiveness makes the algorithm safer and reduces the risk of misread.

column4: Enables/Disables ability to decode Code39 labels

In Code39 decoding, this enables/disables the translation of Code39 characters to Code39 full-ASCII characters.
In the Wand Emulation interface, this enables/disables the Code39 full-ASCII encoding scheme for Code39 labels.
Specifies one of the barcode lengths for Code39 length control.
column8: Length 1 is the minimum label length if in variable length mode, or the first fixed length if in fixed length mode. Length includes the barcode s check, data, and full-ASCII shift characters. The length does not include start/stop characters.

column4: Specifies one of the barcode lengths for Code39 length control.
column8: Length 2 is the maximum label length if in variable length mode, or the second fixed length if in fixed length mode. Length includes the barcode s check, data, and full-ASCII shift characters. The length does not include start/stop characters.

column4: Specifies either variable-length decoding or fixed-length decoding for Code39
column8: For variable-length decoding, a minimum and maximum length may be set. For fixed-length decoding, two different lengths may be set.

column8:
Each ISBT128 Identifier has an associated value listed in the table below. The first byte of this configuration item identifies the left ISBT128 label identifier. The second byte of this configuration item identifies the right ISBT 128 label identifier.
Example 1: The left label of a pair starts with &>. The right label of a pair starts with =]. Set the configuration item to 041E to set up the pair.
Example 2: The left label of a pair starts with &{. The right label of a pair starts with =<. Set the configuration item to 1607 to set up the pair.
Set the value to 0x0000 when not using this pair.

labels are ordered first by the configured output filter represented by the six bytes mask, then in random 
order depending on the reading time sequence.
All read labels will be also transmitted as unspecified symbologies eventually present in the volume.
For each label decoded in the volume the HH signal the standard beeper and  led indications.
As mapping table for Symbologies identifier see SRS.

If a volume contains four label that must be decode in Mutltiple Label per Frame and ordered by this sequence:
First Code: Code39; Second Code: Datamatrix; Third Code: Code 128; Fourth Code: Aztec ==> Then Set the value to 0x240E0C4E0000
Example 2:
Set the value to 0x000000000000 when not using the symbolgy ordering the correspondend to option  is Any Type.

column4:
Configures the scanner's reading mode.
Trigger Object Sense is a feature not applicable on 2D readers. This value is accepted for compatibility with 1D readers but the system composed by 2D HH behave as in default option Trigger Single.
column6:
[format=selection]
0x00=Trigger Single
0x01=Trigger hold multiple
0x02=Trigger pulse multiple
0x03=Flashing
0x04=Always on
0x05=Object Detection
0x06=Trigger Object sense
0x07=Retained Trigger Hold Multiple
column8:
Trigger Single:
When trigger is pulled, scanning is activated and the aiming pattern and the illuminator swicth ON, until CI_ELAPSE_TIME has elapsed, or label has been read, or trigger is released.
While in Trigger Single
 -The Motion Sense is active by default (Motion Aiming Control, CI_MOTION_AIMING_CONTROL ) and if the scanner detects motion the aiming pattern is turned on. When the trigger is pulled, illumination is turned on and the scanner attempts to read a label.
- The pick mode CI_PICK_MODE_ENABLE can Enabled/Disabled.
While in all other Reading Modes:
Trigger hold multiple
Trigger pulse multiple
Flashing 
Always on
Object Detection
- The Motion Sense is always not active except for the Stand Mode when the scanner is not docked.
- The pick mode CI_PICK_MODE_ENABLE is not configurable.
Trigger hold multiple:
When trigger is pulled, scanning is activated until CI_ELAPSE_TIME has elapsed, or the trigger is released. CI_DOUBLE_READ_TIMEOUT gates double reads while in this mode. 
Trigger pulse multiple:
When trigger is pulled, scanning is activated and continues after trigger is released until CI_ELAPSE_TIME has elapsed, or the trigger pulled again. CI_DOUBLE_READ_TIMEOUT gates double reads while in this mode.
Flashing:
The Illuminator flashes on and off regardless of the trigger status. Flash rate is controlled by CI_FLASH_ON and CI_FLASH_OFF.
Always on:
The illuminator is always on and and the reader always ready for reading. 
CI_DOUBLE_READ_TIMEOUT gates double reads while in this mode.
Object Detection (Stand mode):
When in this mode the scanner looks for scene changes within its field-of-view. The Aiming Pattern is always on to help the user to find the right position of the reading area. If a predetermined amount of change in the scene is detected the reader switches the red illumination on. Scanning continues until a label is read or the "maximum scan on time" is reached.
While in Stand Mode, if the trigger is pulled, scanner acts as if in single read mode. CI_DOUBLE_READ_TIMEOUT gates double reads.
Additional Notes:
- Trigger Object sense is a feature not applicable, even is option value in a BT system
  is accepted by base station. That value is accepted for compatibility with 1D readers but the 
 system composed by 2D HH BT behave as: in default option Trigger Single.
- All decoding options like Inverse Reading or Multiple Reading can be configured regardless the reading mode option selected.
- The Tag name for option value:
0x05=Stand Mode changed into
0x05=Object Detection within the first maintenance release. (called stand mode till Columbus M86)

column8:
Used by the keyboard wedge interface.
KBNL is used only in HA11 and HA29 because those two interfaces need numbers to be used together with ALT key to get the final character.
As described into 61717 defect:
KBD-AT (HA10) has to be used with external PS/2 keyboard connected, this interface doesn't use KBNL because character are "directly pressed"
KBD-AT-ALT (HA29) has to be used with external PS/2 keyboard connected, this interface uses KBNL because it emulates all characters with ALT+numbers
KBD-AT-NK (HA26) has to be used without external PS/2 keyboard connected, this interface doesn't use KBNL because character are "directly pressed"
KBD-AT-ALT-NK (HA11) has to be used without external PS/2 keyboard connected, this interface uses KBNL because it emulates all characters with ALT+numbers, but you can not see the BlocNum toggled because there's no connected keyboard.
The item shall be defined for class 6 because the presence of KBD-AT-ALT and KBD-AT-ALT-NK, but it is useless for other two interfaces.

column8: Changing this value from the factory setting may be necessary when connecting two of the same scanner type to a POS system.

column4: When set to Ignore, the scanner will ignore all host commands except for those necessary for service mode, flash programming mode, to keep the interface active, and transmit labels.
column8:
The options value description coming form the past revision and Museo platform was:
0x00=Normal (Do not ignore host commands)
0x01=Ignore
The current value have been updated to:
0x00=Obey (Do not ignore host commands)
0x01=Ignore

column4: Specifies maximum number of data characters in a host transmit message.
column8:
This value cannot be set above 246 because the scanner cannot verify a message length in that range due to the data length limitations of the IPC_UI_Xmit_Data_Cmd specified in "System Controller / Universal Interface IPC Specification", R90-0046. 
In general, this length excludes the framing bytes, if they exist, of the selected interface. See the Comet EDD for details about the data bytes included in this length for each interface.

column4: Provides for an interface specific control mechanism.
column6:
[format=selection]
0x00=Obey Scanner Configuration Host Commands
0x02=Ignore Scanner Configuration Host Commands
[PRG_ValueIncluded=false]
column8:
Selects the following options in the specfied interfaces:
USB OEM -
  Bit0: 1 = Compatible with MagellanSL Configuration Host Cmd Processing. 0 = Normal Processing.
  Bit1: 1 = Fake Scanner Configuration Host Cmd Processing. 0 = Normal Processing.
  Bit2: 1 = Fake Scale Configuration Host Cmd Processing. 0 = Normal Processing.
IBM 4683 Port 5B - 
  Bit0: Unused
  Bit1: 1 = Fake Scanner Configuration Host Cmd Processing. 0 = Normal Processing.
  Bit2: Unused
IBM 4683 Port 9B - 
  Bit0: Unused
  Bit1: 1 = Fake Scanner Configuration Host Cmd Processing. 0 = Normal Processing.
  Bit2: Unused
RS232 -
  All bits unused.
Keyboard -
  All bits unused.
USB-HID-POS -
  All bits unused.
Wand -
  All bits unused.

column4: Specifies whether [Apple iOS]-specific character conversion must be enabled or disabled. Useful when using BT HID.
column8: It is suggested to enable this feature when the scanner must work using BT HID with a remote device running Apple iOS operating system. Especially if the remote language and the scanner language is German.

column8:
If this configuration item is 00 and CI_ALL_AIM_ID_ENABLE is enabled and doing EAN128 or Code 128 emulation, the MicroPDF AIM Id type is used (]L3, ]L4 or ]L5).
If this configuration item is 00, and doing EAN128 or Code 128 emulation, the label type remains MicroPDF. CI_ALL_AIM_ID_ENABLE must be disabled.
If this configuration item is 01 CI_ALL_AIM_ID_ENABLE is enabled and doing EAN128 or Code 128 emulation, the Code 128 / EAN 128 AIM Id type is used (]C0, ]C1 or ]C2). 
If this configuration item is 01, and doing EAN128 or Code 128 emulation, the label type is changed to either EAN128 or Code 128. CI_ALL_AIM_ID_ENABLE must be disabled.

Converts transmission characters from one value to another.
column8:
There are 8 characters in this conversion string: Characters [1] [2] [3] [4] [5] [6] [7] [8].
The following conversions occur:
Character [1] is converted to Character [2]; If Character [1] is 0xFF, there is no conversion.
Character [3] is converted to Character [4]; If Character [3] is 0xFF, there is no conversion.
Character [5] is converted to Character [6]; If Character [5] is 0xFF, there is no conversion.
Character [7] is converted to Character [8]; If Character [7] is 0xFF, there is no conversion.

column4: This configuration items allows certain testing features to be enabled or disabled.

This allows software test the ability to control certain operation in the scanner for testing purposes only. The default value of this configuration item as built is zero. 
Bit 0 : 0 = no beeper indication on service mode entry; 1 = beeper indicatin on service mode entry
Bit 1 : Reserved
Bit 2 : 1=disable trigger debounce logic, 0=enable trigger debounce logic

column4: Specifies the way the Radio frequencies are used in an RF Star system
column8:
Star 915 MHz version
	High Speed  STCP = 0x03 (default)
		Default channel   STFA = 0x00 – 910.00 Mhz
		Fixed channels :  12 channels - STFA :  0x01  to  0x0C
		Frequency Hopping :  STFA = 0x80
	Low Speed  STCP = 0x01
		Default channel   STFA = 0x00 – 910.00 Mhz
		Fixed channels :  25 channels - STFA :  0x01  to  0x19
		Frequency Hopping : STFA = 0x80
Star 433 MHz version
	High Speed  STCP = 0x03 (default)
		Default channel   STFA = 0x00 – 433.92 Mhz
		Fixed channels :  Only the default channel STFA 0x00
		Frequency Hopping :  Not supported (one channel only in band)
	Low Speed  STCP = 0x01
		Default channel   STFA = 0x00 – 433.92 Mhz
		Fixed channels :  5 channels -  STFA :  0x01  to  0x05
		Frequency Hopping : STFA = 0x80
No other settings are allowed.
High order number (@ in Aladdin Menu Path) to be always put after Radio Common items.

column8:

column4: Configures the operative mode of the  Arrow Keys.

Configure the Arrow Keys functionality type. Two options are available:
Function Keys Action Select mode:
When in this mode, arrow keys are used to select one of the 3 possible actions associated to the Function Keys. To associate actions to the Function keys, see "Configure Actions for Function keys".
String Association Mode:
When in this mode, each one of the arrow keys can be programmed to display and transmit a pre-defined string, see "Arrow Up String (4-key models only)" "Arrow Down String (4-key models only)".

Order is as follows 
- 4 keys: K0, K1, K2, K3, x, x,  x  x (where x = ignored) 
K0 = Arrow up, 
K1 = F2, 
K2 = F1, 
K3 = Arrow down
- 16 keys: K0, K1  K15
K0  = SHIFT
K1  = F4
K2  = 4
K3  = 8
K4  = F1
K5  = 1
K6  = 5
K7  = 9
K8  = F2
K9  = 2
K10 = 6
K11 = 0
K12 = F3
K13 = 3
K14 = 7
K15 = RETURN
